PAPERLESS ORDER ON PRETRIAL AND DISCOVERY

All parties are ordered to follow the pretrial and discovery timeline. The Pretrial window will end in 10 (Ten) days till March 21, 2025 at 9:44 p.m.. All parties are required to have their pre-trial motions submitted to this court 48 hours before the start of trial.

It is further ORDERED AND ADJUDGED that the Court confirms the State's obligation to disclose to the defendant all exculpatory evidencenamely, evidence that favors the defendant or casts doubt on the State's caseas required by the principles established in Brady v. Maryland, 373 U.S. 83 (1963) and its progeny. The State is hereby ORDERED to fulfill this obligation. The State has a duty to disclose any evidence that negates the defendant's guilt, affects the credibility of a witness, or could potentially reduce a sentence. The defendant is entitled to this information without needing to make a request. Failure to disclose exculpatory evidence in a timely manner may result in consequences, including, but not limited to, exclusion of evidence, dismissal of the information, contempt proceedings, disciplinary action, or sanctions by the Court.
